summary: I do not believe, by the way, that aziraphale and crowley were ever actual enemies bent on destroying each other. at MOST they...
body: I do not believe, by the way, that aziraphale and crowley were ever actual enemies bent on destroying each other. at MOST they were awkward acquaintances who knew they weren’t supposed to like each other but couldn’t help it. crowley doesn’t have the stomach to cause any of the particularly evil things humans do and aziraphale has too much faith in crowley to really believe he’d be capable of it. like maybe once or twice he ran into crowley at the site of some horrific event and narrowed his eyes and asked if crowley had caused it, more for show than because he thinks crowley might have had a hand in it, but they were pretty friendly all the way back in eden and I see no reason that would have changed at any point except for the better

title: Good Omens Quote
body: Aziraphale collected books. If he were totally honest with himself he would have to have admitted that his bookshop was simply somewhere to store them. He was not unusual in this. In order to maintain his cover as a typical second-hand book seller, he used every means short of actual physical violence to prevent customers from making a purchase. Unpleasant damp smells, glowering looks, erratic opening hours—he was incredibly good at it.

body:
Late to the party

…but I’m finally reading Good Omens and good heavens, David Tennant truly is the perfect Crowley. I can already hear the dialogue in his voice, because it just works so flawlessly.

I’m obviously quite embarrassed that I’m just now starting the book, but I’m also rather happy that I waited, because now I have the absolutely perfect mental cast to work with.
